The StringTokenizer class in Java is used to break a string into tokens. The tokens are obtained by splitting the string using a delimiter. In this case, the delimiter is a comma, left parenthesis, right parenthesis, and a space. 

The first token is obtained by calling nextToken() method of StringTokenizer class. Then, the second token is obtained by calling nextToken() method again. And the third token is obtained by calling nextToken() method one more time.

Please note that the tokens are obtained in the order they are found in the string. So, the first token is the 1st value, the second token is the 2nd value, and the third token is the 3rd value.

Also, please note that the StringTokenizer class is deprecated in Java 9 and removed in Java 11. If you are using Java 9 or 10, you should consider using the java.util.Scanner class or the java.util.regex.Pattern class for tokenizing strings.
